postcontent:
I have for sale one unopened box of .357 Mag Black Talon ammo.  The 20-round box is clean and complete.  The 180-grain bullet has a deep hollow point which is scored to ensure rapid expansion upon impact.

Black Talon ammunition was introduced by Winchester Ammunition in 1991 primarily for law enforcement and self-defense. This hollow-point ammunition became known for its bullet's unique construction and sharp petal shape after expansion following impact with tissue or other wet media.

Black Talon pistol loads are not loaded to higher working pressures or higher velocity "+P" loadings.

Winchester discontinued the Black Talon line completely in 2000.  Here is your chance to pick up a box of this rare and desireable ammo.  I no longer have a revolver that shoots it, so it needs a new home.  Please contact me immediately, since it won't last long at this price.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga-M rifle .223 Remington
postcontent:
I have for sale a Saiga-M rifle in .223 Remington. This is not a VEPR from MOLOT, but a Saiga from the famous Izmash factory in Russia. Imported by the Russian American Armory Company. From what I've read, there were not a lot of these imported (around 5,000?) so they are somewhat rare, and not easy to find.
This is NOT like the Saiga rifles that you see sold for $349 on some websites or in gun shops.  If that's what you want, think this is the same as, or are looking for, keep moving please...

This is basically an unconverted modernized version of the Saiga sporting rifle/ carbines, but with a heavier receiver and barrel. I've been told the receiver is similar to that on an RPK strength-wise, but I don't know for sure.

This rifle has:

-heavy duty receiver with slant cut rear
-21" hammer forged chrome-lined heavy barrel
- 300m rear sight leaf, standard AK type front post
-integrated side mount scope rail
-beautiful polished Walnut thumbhole stock with raised cheek rest, and rubber butt pad
-I've replaced the factory sling swivel mounts with Uncle Mike's studs and KNS 1.25" sling swivels.

Rifle comes with:
(1) Saiga factory 10rd magazine
(1) SGM 10rd magazine
(1) SGM 15rd magazine

Unfortunately, it doesn't use .223 AK magazines, just mags made specifically for it and the other Saiga rifles. They're not uncommon, and I've found them for around $20-30 on the 'net, and you can buy 10,15, 20, or even 30 rounders.

This is an extremely nice rifle, and is a blast to shoot. It is accurate, and even though the factory guarantees a 3 MOA  @ 100yds accuracy, I've shot a 2 MOA group @ 100yds with iron sights, and a 1.5 MOA group @ 200yds with a 4-16x40 scope, both from benchrest.

I figure this would make someone a nice hunting rifle, or just a good all around rifle for that matter with the very common .223 cartridge. I've had it to the range maybe 4-5 times, and put probably 200-300 rds through it, with no jams, misfeeds or FTE's. Eats any ammo I feed it with no problem. Has some very minor surface blemishes and scratches, mostly from the safety. I think it has very nice flowing lines, and still captures the classic look and function of an AK.

I'm asking for $475 cash, and I'm pretty firm on that, but I am a reasonable guy and I may do a little negotiating on price. Make an offer, all I can say is no. I'm not really in a hurry to sell, just making room in the safe.

FTF transaction, FL resident, ID required, and a CCW is a bonus. As for travel, I live around Eustis/Mt. Dora, but I'm in the Lake Mary/Sanford area daily. I will not travel more than 20-25 miles from home for a deal.

If you're interested, contact me through this site.

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Lowered Price Snubnose 7 shot Hard Chrome Plated Revolver 100.00
postcontent:
This is a very unique Russian Variation of  the Nagant model 1895 revolver which started life as what is known a really rare " Nagant Short"
They were Extremely rare variations of the Russian Nagant revolvers which had a Shortened frame and barrel and these were issued to N.K.V.D. officers and special agents.
What makes this gun even cooler is it has been hard chrome plated and the barrel shortened even more making it a snub nose. The sight was removed and the barrell professionally cut shorter and the front sight reinstalled. It is a great shooter and the 7 shot capacity makes it even more fun and better equipped for a carry gun. 
I know that these can be bought new for around 150.00 in the standard long barrel but the fact it has been made into a snub nose and chrome plated I think is definately worth the extra 100 bucks Im asking over the typical Nagant,
Due to the gas block cylinder design this gun could be suppressed or silenced and is the only revolver i know of due to the normal cylinder air gap on all others that makes the nagant the only revolver made that can be suppressed and since you wouldnt have to pick up the empty brass just imagine the coolness of such a suppressed revolver. Ive shot a couple of suppressed nagants and they are truly way more quiet than a semi auto because you dont hear the noise of the slide.

The chrome has some spots that are not perfect. I would rate the gun at probally 75 percent but it is good and tight and the timing perfect and shoots a good tight group
I can text or email pics upon request
Please call or text Dave at 865=201==0039

title: For Sale:  Hungarian FEG AP MBP Pistol .32ACP
postcontent:
Hungarian FEG AP MBP Pistol .32ACP single/double action just like the pistols themselves are almost straight Walther PP copies with an aluminum frame.These were Hungarian-made, F.E.G. pistols sold throughout Europe from the late 1960's to the mid-Eighties. Most were made to be sold commercially, but I'm sure some were used by the Communist Hungarian police forces for the walking beat cop. The caliber is the key, .32acp, up until the mid-1970's the "common" police caliber in most of Europe. The F.E.G. PA-63 in 9x18mm Makarov was supposed to have been a Hungarian Military sidearm only.

ASKING $250 CASH AS IS 

TEXT/EMAIL REDACTED

The M951XM07 Millennium® Universal WeaponLight is a 6-volt (two-battery) WeaponLight that attaches by means of an integral dual thumbscrew clamp to long guns equipped with a Picatinny rail. The compact, shock-isolated incandescent lamp/reflector assembly produces a tactical-level beam with good reach and excellent peripheral light, perfectly suited for interior and close-range applications. It produces 65 lumens for one-hour of runtime using the P60 lamp assembly (included) or 120 lumens for 20 minutes using the P61 lamp assembly (optional). The FM63 is an infrared (IR) filter for flashlights and WeaponLights with a 1.47" diameter bezel. Cancels out the non-infrared portion of the light spectrum to produce a smooth beam of infrared light for use with night vision devices and infrared-capable video cameras. For military or law enforcement infrared applications, SureFire also recommends the M1 Illuminator, as its dedicated infrared design may be more appropriate for mission critical tasking. Applying thumb pressure to the locking tab releases the cover; a spring mechanism keeps the open cover out of the way by holding it flat against the flashlight.
